WHO   — THE ZILOG Z80 — an exereunesis sphere — the teardown
WHAT  — Designed by Federico Faggin's Zilog, the Z80 was an 8-bit CPU compatible with the Intel 8080 but with more registers and instructions — and it became one of the longest-lived processors ever. It ran CP/M computers, countless arcade boards, the Master System, the Game Gear, and the MSX standard.
WHERE — the teardown — a made machine, opened and explored  Framework inputs: the chips; the buses; the spec; the lore  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — Designed by Federico Faggin's Zilog, the Z80 was an 8-bit CPU compatible with the Intel 8080 but with more registers and instructions — and it became one of the longest-lived processors ever. It ran CP/M computers, countless arcade boards, the Master System, the Game Gear, and the MSX standard.
HOW   — Rendered from the public technical record.

